Stylish is awesome for that, 'though it's only <i>really</i> useful if you know CSS.<p>I have a theme for HN with this:<p><pre><code>    @-moz-document domain("news.ycombinator.com") {
      .default {
        max-width: 45em;
        text-align: justify;
      }
    }
</code></pre>
Solves the problem really cleanly.<p>I don't really go to Reddit anymore, but you can use:<p><pre><code>    .usertext-body { max-width: 45em; }
</code></pre>
to fix the extra large lines, and hiding the sidebar can be done with:<p><pre><code>    .side { display: none }
</code></pre>
By the way, this is one of the best advantages of websites over native apps: it's much easier to tame them to your needs. Even if you don't know how to program it yourself, <a href="http://userscripts.org" rel="nofollow">http://userscripts.org</a> and <a href="http://userstyles.org" rel="nofollow">http://userstyles.org</a> are incredible resources.
